\b \cf2 Situation in Germany\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl220\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 In the year 2015 several tomographs (Positron Emission Tomography and Single-Photon-Emissions-Tomography) from Siemens had been used in german hospitals. At that time it was already common that the tomographs had security holes such as they were easy to hack by attackers from outside the network. One reason for that danger has been the operation system under which the tomography had been running. As the US agency ICS-CERT (Industrial Control Systems Cyber Emergency Response Team) has published that there had been security holes in tomographs from Siemens they also mentioned that one of the main risks had been Windows 7. Furthermore there were so-called \'93Exploits-Coder\'93 which can be used without any expert knowledge. As a consequence, attackers can \'93speak\'94 over the network with the devices by accessing the network of the hospital. As a solution, Siemens has claimed that there will be available \'93security updates\'94 for all affected tomographs. But in fact, they only mentioned the updates as a brief security note. Actually, the date (until which day) the patches will be available for users had not been published yet.\
